Drinking about 2 pounds a day can reduce the risk of heart attack.
Thousands of patients who have had a heart attack could be treated with the drug for 2 pounds a day, as official representatives recommend taking it to more people and for a longer period of time.
The anticoagulant drug Ticagrelor reduces the risk of recurring heart attacks in people with heart disease.
These drugs are already prescribed for use 12 months after a heart attack, reducing the risk of a recurrent heart attack.
NICE, represented by the NHS, recommends taking this preparation 4 years after a heart attack to further reduce the risk of heart attack in people with cardiovascular problems.
However, the NHS currently managed NICE recommends taking this preparation 4 years after a heart attack to further reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease.
Every year, about 140,000 people in England experience a heart attack and a quarter of them experience a recurrent heart attack or stroke.
Heart attack and stroke are caused by the accumulation of fatty substances in the walls of the heart, forming blockages.
If the blockage breaks, it can cause a thrombus, blocking the flow of blood to the heart and causing a heart attack.
In turn, if the thrombus separates from the blood vessel wall, it can go further into the bloodstream and block blood access to the brain, causing a heart attack.
People who have had a heart attack are at higher risk of recurring heart attacks.
Ticagrelor, manufactured by the British company AstraZeneca and marketed under the name Brilique, reduces the risk of thrombosis.
The new NICE guidelines, published today, recommend people to take 90 mg of Ticagrelor for 12 months and another 3 years at 60 mg twice a day along with aspirin.
NICE Director of Health Technology Professor Kerola Longson explains: “Despite the availability of medications to prevent recurrent heart attacks, more than a quarter of people who have had a heart attack experience another heart attack or stroke, which often has severe consequences.”
Fear of a recurring heart attack can leave a negative impact on a person’s quality of life.
Evidence suggests that Ticagrelor in combination with aspirin effectively reduces the risk of recurring heart attacks and heart attacks in people who have already experienced it.
By provisionally recommending treatment with Ticagrelor, we are pleased to be able to extend treatment options to thousands of people, which is thus beneficial.
Given the limited information on the effectiveness and safety of Ticagrelor, especially the risk of bleeding when using this drug for more than three years, the draft guidelines do not recommend using it for longer than this period.
