German researchers discuss the number of "victims of the Berlin Wall".
According to a new study, the number of deaths near the former East German border may be much higher than previously thought, but doubts about the real number of victims are still not cleared.
According to data released on Wednesday by the Berlin Wall Museum, Checkpoint Charlie, between 1945 and 1989, 1841 people were murdered at the border with allied zones and later communist authorities in West Germany in an attempt to escape their territory.
The museum has been investigating border-related deaths for years and is adjusting the number of victims from time to time.
This year, 11 more deaths were added to the list, including a six-year-old boy who drowned while his family tried to get to West Germany through then-Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
Among the new victims of the Berlin Wall are Soviet deserters.
"The ultimate extent of the damage caused by the double evil of communism and socialism has not yet been fully documented," admits museum director Alexandra Hildebrante.
"Our task is to ensure that the graves of those who died trying to flee a communist-controlled country are cleaned up and not destroyed," Hildebrant said in a statement.
However, other researchers have already questioned the new figures.
"The number 1841 is unconvincing," said John Stath, an expert on East German history at the Free University of Berlin, in an interview with the Süddeutsche Zeitung.
He and other researchers at the Free University of Berlin are currently reviewing possible suspicious deaths at the border, and so far they have only managed to confirm 260 cases.
Previously, researchers estimated that 138 people were murdered by the Communists at the Berlin Wall alone.
Taking into account the number of people who died trying to flee the Baltic Sea or get to the West through the territory of neighboring countries, according to the State, the number of victims could reach about a thousand.
However, this is significantly less than in 1841.
One of the reasons for the different numbers of victims could be different methodologies.
The Checkpoint Charlie Museum also lists all cases of suicide by East German border guards, whether or not they were directly related to their service.
The museum also lists deaths that are not directly related to violence.
“If seniors aged 70 to 80 died of a heart attack after collapsing with border controls, it must be the consequences of this ‘murderous boundary’,” says Hildebrante.
But the State is convinced that there should be a distinction between old people who may have died as a result of their treatment and those whose deaths were caused by long waiting in hot weather on the bus at the border.
Regardless, the counting of victims is not easy, as the communist authorities of East Germany did not collect such statistics, and researchers must search the documents in various scattered archives, state said.
However, the State Group has recently obtained new documents, so it could soon come up with a new estimate of the number of victims.
