A French court has rejected the demolition of shops in the "Jungle" refugee camp.
A French court has rejected a request by the authorities in Calais to demolish dozens of self-constructed shops and restaurants in the "Jungle" camp where thousands of refugees live.
At a court hearing in Calais this week, authorities stated that the state should demolish 72 self-made stores, where in the camp area people trade various goods such as cigarettes and energy drinks, offer hairdresser services, tea for 50 cents (40p) and simple meals for a few euros in self-made restaurants.
The prefect’s office in Kalye pointed out that these self-established companies must be demolished as they form a shadow economy and do not pay taxes, and also pose fire and sanitary risks.
Representatives of the humanitarian group explained to the court that these small are critical because the food provided by governments and support groups do not meet the needs of the camp, where the population continues to grow.
They also pointed out that self-made shops and restaurants often offer free shelter and food to those who need it most.
The Lille court ruled that there was no legal basis to expel people who had set up 72 self-made stores, but it understood the Prefect’s concerns.
Judge Jean-François Molla said food, coffee and restaurants play a bigger role than just providing food to people who live in “extremely harsh conditions.”
He pointed out that these places are peaceful meetings for refugees and volunteers.
One of the places at risk of demolition is the camp cafe "Jungle Book Kids", which provides more than 200 free meals a day, English and French lessons, and provides asylum advice to hundreds of vulnerable minors without adult escort.
More than 170,000 people have signed a petition to protect children’s cafes.
