In Spain, the potential to reduce the budget deficit is threatened by the failure to form a government.
On July 12, the European Commission (EC) ruled that Spain and Portugal had not taken sufficient measures to reduce their budget deficit to 3% of the euro area’s gross domestic product (GDP).
Despite the austerity measures implemented, the budget deficit in Portugal at the end of last year was 4.4% of GDP, while in Spain it was 5.1%.
The European Commission has decided not to impose economic sanctions on the two countries, but has set fiscal targets for the near future.
One of the reasons why the Commission has failed to impose sanctions on both countries is the growing euroscepticism in many EU countries.
Additional sanctions would only increase such a negative mood.
Critics, however, point out that the Commission is not consistent in its decisions, agreeing on uniform rules from the outset and then failing to apply them to life.
For example, German Bundesbank President Jens Weidmann said that Europe thus loses confidence in itself, giving citizens the impression that the rules of the European Union are recommendative rather than binding.
The Commission has now proposed and all Member States have agreed to extend the budget deficit settlement deadline until the end of this year for Portugal and until 2018 for Spain.
The European Commission has pledged to test the progress made by both countries in the coming months, but said both Spain and Portugal should be prepared to introduce additional austerity measures if circumstances require it.
Preliminary forecasts indicate that Portugal could be able to meet its targets on time and the budget deficit could be reduced to 2.5 percent of GDP this year.
This means that within the framework of the Stability Program, the government of this country has to implement austerity measures of 0.25% of GDP this year.
These measures should be included in this year’s budget, with a further focus on controlling the cost of procurement of goods and services.
In Spain, the situation is much more complicated.
This year the budget deficit should be reduced to 4.6%, next year - to 3.1% and in 2018 - to 2.2% of GDP.
In addition, for the next two years, consolidation measures should be at an annual level of 0.5% of GDP.
