The cleanliness of the beaches in the Gulf of Riga is critical.
During the fifth year of surveys of the beaches, activists concluded that unfortunately the number of waste found is increasing every year, and this is mostly the guilt of swimming pool visitors.
The most polluted swimming areas are in Riga.
The capital government explains that swimming pools are cleaned every day, but fighting against dirty visitors is quite difficult.
In addition, waste left on land can be swallowed into water during rains, thereby significantly deteriorating its quality.
With the exception of Liepaja beaches and certain places in Kurzem, the cleanliness of the beaches elsewhere in Latvia is critical.
This was announced this week by volunteers from the “My Sea” campaign.
During the five-year walk along the Gulf of Riga, activists concluded that the number of waste left by the population has increased every hundred meters.
Unfortunately, this year the critical assessment has entered.
“We see that this will be the year when the amount of waste on the 100 meters of the beach may even exceed 200 units,” says Janis Ulme, a representative of the expedition “My Sea”.
Called by Latvian Radio, he was on the beach of Tuja, where the volunteer march continues along the Gulf of Riga.
This year, among various household garbage and picnic remains, activists even had to collect daylight bulbs left in the sea sand.
The participant and organizer of the tour Ulme said that the people are responsible for the pollution.
“The main source is the beach visitors themselves, as more than half of the total waste is plastic, various waste, ranging from bags, pieces of plastic that are already in the degradation stage, they can no longer be identified, and smokes, bottles, curls,” says Ulme.
Among the dirty beaches there are also swimming spots in Riga.
For example, in Daugavgry, on average, almost 800 units of waste are collected per hundred meters, which is critical.
Campaign organizers also explain that smokers are also put on almost every step and no warning or prohibition signs are placed everywhere.
“The average figures for all three Riga bathing sites together – Daugavgrivu, Vakarbuļļi and Vecāki – are unfortunately high and far exceed the desired or target, to which Latvia is allegedly moving, to reduce the number of waste units to 135 units by 2020,” concludes the environmental defender.
Bathroom cleaning in Riga takes place every day, even twice in the hottest days of summer, explains the representative of the Duma Uģis Vidauskis.
However, dealing with dirty visitors is quite difficult.
Let us return to the culture of these people.
“Those who drink, drink, smoke and do all the things that are not allowed to do, even special signs do not work,” Vidauskis said.
Therefore, Vidauskis urges swimming sites visitors to report pollutants to the police as well.
You can call the police, safely point to these violations and in this way all fight.
There may be some new warnings, but, as I said, it is unlikely that this will radically change the situation.
“Because everyone together should simply turn and be intolerant to such offenders,” he emphasizes.
Meanwhile, water quality measurements have been carried out this summer for the fourth time by the Health Inspectorate, which may impose a ban on official bathing sites.
This year, as in all other years, the quality of the water is good and satisfying.
Currently, the situation is such that the water quality of all 56 swimming pools has been good all the time and there are no swimming restrictions.
"The last time we will take the analyses will be in late August," said the inspection's senior specialist for environmental health Normunds Kadiček.
During heavy rains, waste left on land can be swallowed into water.
This, in turn, can affect its quality, says an environmental expert.
