The renovation of the VEF Cultural Palace will finally begin this week.
The castle will be rebuilt for approximately 11 million euros.
Several rooms of the castle are planned to be renovated, including two auditoriums, as well as the building to be adapted to people with disabilities.
Riga Duma intends to attract six million euros from European Union funds for the project, but Riga Duma’s Property Department Director Oleg Burov admits that for now there is no clarity about the European funds for the project.
“Despite the political will to start repairs at the VEF Cultural Palace by attracting European structural funds, we have been waiting for months for a decision, real action from the officials of the Ministry of Finance, whether the money will be granted or not,” says Burov.
We were told last December that it all depends on Brussels.
Two weeks ago, the Ministry of Finance received a letter from the European Commission to make its own decision that Brussels will not make a decision here.
Now we see that another round of discussions is forming again, well, then we will see what we can expect in the coming days.
“I want to say that the Riga Council without a doubt guarantees that this process will be started and completed on time,” Burov said.
It has already been that more than a year ago, in March 2015, the VEF Cultural Palace collectively held a farewell concert before the immediate, upcoming renovation of the building.
Although a year has passed, the renovation of the building has not yet begun and collectively continued to work under inappropriate conditions.
In the strategy of the Riga Duma Property Department, the renovation of the VEF Cultural Palace is divided into seemingly independent reconstruction sets, where each will ensure the implementation of different palace functions.
The first is to increase the accessibility of the VEF Cultural Palace and improve the surrounding area.
It is intended to arrange the neighborhood and engineering communications, as well as to restore the facade of the building.
The second is to improve the offer of VEF Cultural Palace services.
It plans to improve the interior of the building, the restoration of walls and ceilings, the stage and sound recording studio, as well as to arrange the internal engineering communications of the building.
Third - Improving the working conditions of creative amateur collectives, which includes plans to improve the equipment of the workshops, room heating and ventilation systems.
Before the 40th anniversary of "Līvu" the legendary rock band can be seen in the exhibition in Liepaja.
The exhibition will showcase various "Līvus" characteristic objects - photographs that are arranged in a timeline to reflect the group's activities from its beginnings until 2010, when the group's end is announced.
The participants will also be shown stage costumes, musical instruments, awards and concert papers, as well as other things not yet seen by the general public, which reflected the creative activity of the group "Livi".
The exhibition will be supplemented with items from the Liepaja Museum.
The visual presentation of the exhibition was made in collaboration with the fashion artist and painter Elite Patmalnieci.
Also, musicians who were associated with the group "Livi" and their relatives, appealed to the call and shared both objects and memories.
The origins of "Līvu" can be sought in 1972, when a vocal instrumental ensemble is created in the Liepaja Cultural House, led by Juris Pavítols.
The ensemble participated in its original composition in the festival "Liepājas dzintars" in 1972 and 1974, as well as in city and republic shows.
In 1976, a fateful meeting took place when Juris Pavítols met Erik Kiigeli and founded a group in the Metalurgical Palace of Culture, inviting Ingrīdu Gūtmani, Andri Krūziņu and Jāni Grodumu to join.
Over the years, the composition of the group has been considered not only once.
Participants have joined, others have gone their way, some have returned.
