“In order to desired weight loss results, the right choice of food combinations is very important,” says Lithuanian dietitian Laura Romeraite-Kuklieriene.
In addition, this is easy to do during the summer period, when fresh fruits, berries and vegetables grow in our own gardens.
A thoughtful combination of dietary products can help not only reduce excess weight, but also targetedly promote various processes in the body.
Pasta and vinegar are a successful combination because they provide a long-lasting feeling of satiety and help fight fat.
Studies published in the European Journal of Clinical Nutrition have shown that vinegar has a beneficial effect on blood glucose levels and helps us feel moody.
Cayenne peppers and protein-rich foods, such as poultry meat or protein cocktail, not only produce a feeling of satiety, but also reduce cravings after large meals at subsequent meals.
This combination of foods can increase the amount of calories burned after a meal by up to 35%.
Studies have shown that Cayenne pepper can help get rid of fat in the abdominal area.
The composition of eggs contains a metabolism-enhancing nutrient - choline, while pepper is a good source of vitamin C.
Taking in sufficient amounts of these nutrients can reduce cortisol levels and thus the accumulation of fat around the middle part of the body.
The oatmeal crust, which is added with fresh berries, is another tasty and fat-burning meal for breakfast that is worth including in your menu.
Peas and berries contain fiber, which, according to the findings of Canadian scientists, controls ghrelin – an appetite-stimulating hormone – and thus also the feeling of hunger.
In addition, the berries contain polyphenols, which are assistants in weight reduction and also prevent the formation of fat.
Vegetables and proteins can also do wonders in weight loss.
Such a combination can create a feeling of satiety.
Vegetables contain water and fiber, so they promote a feeling of satiety.
At the same time, proteins slow down the process of digestion and provide a feeling of satiety for a longer time.
For lunch, you can eat chicken with salads or make a protein cocktail from the finished mixture and enjoy it with your favorite vegetables.
What combinations of products to avoid?
Fruit contains sugars - monosaccharides or disaccharides - compounds of one or two molecules.
In contrast, the starch found in vegetables is a polysaccharide.
Fruits break down mechanically in the stomach, while chemically they do not break down until they reach the third or fourth stage in the digestive process that occurs in the intestines.
The hardness is divided into three different stages that begin already in the mouth.
Therefore, it is important not to eat sweet food immediately after a meal.
Eating sweet food immediately after a meal, it is "trapped" in the stomach along with other dishes, where it is not chemically digested and begins to blow up.
Do not eat bread, potatoes, peanuts, bananas, dates or other carbohydrate-containing products along with lemons, lime, oranges, grapefruit, pineapples or other acidic fruits.
The enzyme ptialine, which is found in saliva, works only in an alkaline environment.
Fruit acids not only inhibit the digestion of carbohydrates, but also promote their fermentation.
Do not eat eggs and meat, nuts and meat, cheese and eggs or cheese and nuts, meat and milk, eggs and milk or nuts and milk and similar combinations of protein-rich products in one meal.
Their processing requires different digestive juices, each of which has a different strength, characteristics and time to enter the stomach.
Cranberry, honeymelon, muscatmelon and other melons should always be eaten separately from other dishes.
Melons are not digested if they are in the stomach together with other foods.
Fats in combination with protein-rich products.
Fats form a successful combination with starch, however, the same cannot be said about fats and proteins - fats inhibit the digestion of proteins.
Protein can be combined with a very small amount of fat.
If you consume large amounts of protein-containing products, avoid consuming fat altogether.
This also applies to refreshment - it is not recommended to combine a large amount of nuts (containing proteins) with an entire avocado (containing fats).
Such a combination prevents effective weight reduction.
How to cook better?
"Cooking, thermal processing leads to a significant loss of nutrients - about 15% to 55% of the original nutrient composition of products," says the dietitian.
In most cases, nutrients are lost when foods are boiled in water.
However, the nutritional value of certain foods increases, directly boiling.
After cooking the vegetables, the remaining liquid is recommended to be used for soup preparation - in this case you will not lose the nutrients left in the water, and you will be able to eat them later.
Vegetables are recommended to be cooked, including steaming them.
Thermal treatment significantly increases the bioavailability of lycopene in the composition of tomatoes.
Cooking tomatoes for 30 minutes increases the amount of lycopene by 25%.
Thermal treatment also significantly increases the bioavailability of beta-carotene found in red, yellow, orange plants such as tomatoes, carrots, sweet potatoes and spinach.
Thermal processing of eggs and meat deprives the natural properties of the proteins in them, making them easier to digest.
Also, the thermal processing of meat and eggs makes the iron and other minerals contained in these products more easily absorbed by the body.
Keep in mind that freezing foods can reduce the amount of vitamin C from 10% to up to 90%, but freezing the fiber does not affect it.
Beans in combination with tomatoes can increase iron intake in the body, which in turn provides better brain and muscle function.
Our body absorbs up to 33% less non-blood-creating iron found in plant products such as beans, leaf greens, cereal products, than blood-creating iron found in animal products such as beef, fish and chicken.
You can significantly increase the absorption of non-blood-creating iron in the body by taking non-blood-creating iron-containing foods in the diet along with sources of vitamin C such as oranges, tomatoes and berries.
Vitamin C helps to change non-blood-creating iron so that our body absorbs it more easily.
Iron is necessary for the production of hemoglobin, which provides oxygen delivery to the muscles and brain.
To get the most benefit from salads, add healthy fats to them, such as olive or flaxseed oil.
When preparing sandwiches with salmon, add vitamin D-rich salmon or sardines to non-added yogurt, which is a good source of calcium.
Vitamin D increases the amount of calcium absorbed by the intestines and plays a vital role in the bone formation process.
Oats (as well as other whole grain products) along with sources of vitamin C such as strawberries, strawberries, avocados and other fruits or berries help stabilize cholesterol levels as well as avoid clogging of the arteries.
