The most depressing food in the period of depression is “Sweet Meal”
In March 1933, shortly after being elected president, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat in an oval room to hold a meal.
President Roosevelt tasted delicious culinary delicacies such as the pasta of the beetle or fuagra and the Maryland turtle soup.
But that day his meal was much more modest: filled eggs in tomato sauce, potato sausage and dessert – a slime pudding.
Jane Ziegelman says: “It’s a way to solidarize in cooking with people who have had a very hard time.”
Her husband Andrew Kou adds: "It's also a message to Americans about how they should eat."
A couple from the Brooklyn Heights district are food historians.
Kou’s last book, The Vegetable Soup, describes Chinese cuisine in America, while Ziegelman, in his book, The 97 Apples, describes life through food at a rental house in the lower eastern part of Manhattan.
Their new joint work, The Satisfactory Meal, which will be published by Harper on Tuesday, is a story about American food during the Great Depression.
Showing some solidarity in cooking, they held a meal together by reporters at Eisenberg's Sandwich Shop, a simple lunch diner located in the Flatiron district and operating since 1929 when the Great Depression began.
Mr. Ziegelman, 54, ordered a sandwich with melted cheese and crushed olives, while Mr. Kou, 57, ordered chicken, potato cheese and vegetable salads.
When a reporter ordered a fake rabbit, the couple admitted that his choice was very relevant to the conversation about the Great Depression food.
Mrs. Ziegelman told me that the fake rabbit was very popular.
There was a peanut rabbit, a liver rabbit and a bean rabbit.
They were prepared from the basic ingredient and other ingredients that enriched the meal.
Imagine what it feels like to eat as many peanuts as you want to have in place of lunch.
Mr. Kou was upset.
"It probably seemed like the stomach was full of lead," he added.
In pre-depressive years, the American lunch table resembled the Swedish table, especially in rural areas.
Women cooked food for their husbands-workers, and fresh-cooked snacks were served for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
During the First World War, it was the Americans who sent food to Europeans.The "Sweet Meal" described how the Americans adapted to conditions when America suddenly was no longer a land of abundance.
“At the time, food became the main focus of the American people’s everyday attention,” says Mr. Kou, explaining why he and his wife wanted to write specifically on the subject.
The new budget diets became equally important: unknown foods such as fake rabbits and snacks became everyday, snacks were “a great way to use excess,” Ziegelman noted, as chefs could hide unattractive ingredients under a cream sauce.
Fresh fruits were replaced by cheap dried fruits.
Meat, which has been the main ingredient of American dishes for years, has now become an extremely rare luxury item.
At a time when the number of calories and nutritional value of the food was more important than the taste, new, unprecedented formations were born.
In an ancient cookbook, Mrs. Ziegelman found a recipe for cooking onions filled with peanut butter.
Mr. Kou adds: "It wasn't a popular lunch table supplement."
Ms. Ziegelman emphasizes: “It was surreal.”
Peanut butter and baked onions are not compatible.
Many home recipes applied to difficult times.
Household economists such as Louise Stanley, head of the Federal Office of Household Economics from 1923 to 1943, determined a nation’s eating habits that were not experienced either before or after the Great Depression.
