Latvenergo also follows the process of opening the gas market as a potential trader.
The state-owned energy company Latvenergo follows the process of opening the gas market both as a consumer and as a potential trader, said Ivita Bidere, press secretary of the company.
“The decision on whether Latvenergo will also join the gas market as a dealer in the future will be determined by the model of the gas market and the legal framework that will be established.”
“Therefore, on our part, we are actively involved in the creation and commentary of normative acts, as well as submitting our proposals,” Bider said.
The Ministry of Economy (EM) in cooperation with the Public Service Regulation Commission and the energy company "Latvijas Gāze" has drawn up a draft regulation of the Cabinet of Ministers "Rules of Commerce and Use of Natural Gas" which will change the existing principles of the natural gas market, providing natural gas users the right to freely choose the natural gas dealer from 3 April 2017.
In working on the new regulation of the natural gas market, the EM aims to make the natural gas trading process as simple and understandable as possible.
Therefore, as the most efficient and user-friendly service solution, the "dealer-centric model" has been chosen, in which all activities related to customer service are provided by the dealer - one contract, one invoice and one information and customer service location, leaving the technical issues of the natural gas distribution system to the operator of the distribution system.
A similar solution is currently being implemented in the electricity trade.
After April 3, 2017, those household users who do not want to choose another natural gas dealer will be able to continue to receive natural gas from the existing dealer at a regulated price, thus becoming connected users.
"In this case, the obligation to supply natural gas to related users at a regulated price is imposed on the public trader," the ministry said.
In turn, traders will have to choose a natural gas dealer with whom to conclude a natural gas trade agreement.
