Conserve manufacturer Blue Lagoon’s turnover decreased by 33.8 percent last year.
Conserve manufacturer Blue Lagoon's turnover last year was €4.202 million, which is 33.8% less than a year earlier, while the company's losses fell 5.7 times - to €904.7 thousand, according to the annual financial report published in the Lursoft database.
The company’s management report says that in 2015 the company worked with losses incurred for a number of reasons, including due to the continued lack of circulating funds caused by Unicredit Bank’s departure from the Baltic market, interrupting the previous credit line, and leaving the Blue Lagoon with concluded contracts unable to fulfil them.
As a result, the company did not have enough funds to buy cheaper raw materials in large quantities and get a volume discount.
The bank’s departure from the Latvian market also prevented the company from implementing EU structural fund support projects, which would have allowed the plant to purchase new production equipment and modernize the infrastructure.
Similarly, the company’s financial creators in the past year were negatively affected by rising commodity prices and the unwillingness of customers to pay more for the goods produced by the company.
“Only in the second half of July 2016 customers recognized price changes and were ready to buy goods at the new – highest – prices,” the company’s management said.
Also in 2015, Blue Lagoon began negotiations with potential investors, including the evaluation of the company’s movable and real estate.
Investors have already been to the company’s largest lender, Unicredit Leasing, where the parties have met and discussed possible investment plans.
At the same time, the company’s operations and development were positively influenced by the implementation of the restructuring and optimization plan started in 2014 and 2015.
This plan included the improvement and optimization of technological processes to greater production productivity and capacity.
"A number of installations were purchased to provide a higher production speed," the company's management said.
The management of the Blue Lagoon notes that the equipment purchased in 2016 will allow the company’s plant to fulfill such orders that were not possible before.
The first batch of production that will be produced on this equipment will be ready in August.
Since the intention protocols for the sale of the product have already been signed, all produced will be sold according to the intention protocols.
The new product will increase turnover by about 300 thousand euros a month,” the company’s management said.
The company also plans to sign a cooperation agreement on the supply of fish to Iraq in August 2016.
Blue Lagoon sent its first experimental container to Israel in 2016, expanded its sales market to Cyprus and will sign a cooperation agreement with a new supermarket chain in the United States in September this year.
As a result of all the above measures, the company plans to increase its turnover.
In 2014, Blue Lagoon operated with a turnover of EUR 6,347 million and a loss of EUR 5,113 million.
Blue Lagoon was founded in 1997 and has a capital of €1.156 million.
The company is owned by two Latvian individuals – Mikhail Kaidanov (89.11%) and Igor Shirshon (10.89%).
