NASA climate model: Venus was once a habitable planet
Based on NASA’s latest climate models, Venus has once been a habitable planet.
Scientists at NASA’s Goddard Space Research Institute have developed a model to study the history of Venus using tools and algorithms used by climate scientists.
The model was developed to determine whether Venus, whose surface is hot, where there is no water and whose atmosphere consists almost entirely of carbon, has ever had conditions similar to Earth.
Scientists have previously speculated that the slow rotation of Venus can be explained by its dense atmosphere.
However, recent simulations suggest that Venus once had a flat, Earth-like atmosphere and that it rotated slowly.
The model also looks at the earlier topography of Venus.
There were more dry areas on the planet than on Earth, but there was enough water and geographical diversity on it to form life and prevent water from evaporating.
In the early days of Venus, the Sun was 30 percent brighter.
In a GISS model simulation, the rotating model of Venus reveals that the light part of the day on it lasts for 2 months, GISS scientist Antonio Del Genio explained in a press release.
This process warms the surface of the planet and causes the matter, which in turn forms layers of thick clouds that act as a rainbow, protecting the planet from solar heat.
As a result, a temperate climate temperature is formed, which is actually a few degrees lower than the temperature on Earth today.
The model depicts the history of Venus, which is similar to the theory of evolution developed by scientists in their hypotheses.
Although it was once habitable, Venus has been exposed to excessive heat and ultraviolet rays for several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated, and the garlands were burned by ultraviolet rays.
When the water completely evaporated, only a thin carbon dioxide atmosphere with a deadly greenhouse gas remained – Venus as we know it today.
Scientists published the results of the new Venus climate model in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
