Kepler measured the speed of rotation of stars in the Pleiadian constellation.
The latest Kepler telescope mission has helped astronomers compile the most comprehensive catalogue of the speed of rotation of stars in the Plejadic constellation.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars in this constellation rotate at different speeds, and how the speed of star rotation can be attributed to planet formation.
“We hope that by comparing our results with other constellations, we will get more insight into the relationship between the masses of the stars, their age and even the history of their solar system,” said Luisa Rebula, a scientist at the Caltech Infrared Process and Analysis Center at Pasadena.
The Plejad constellation is 445 light-years away from Earth.
Many stars in this constellation are just beginning to rise, reaching about 125 million years of age.
It rotates at maximum speed.
At their maximum speed, these rising stars emit large amounts of star wind.
When winds enter the star's magnetic field, they brake the stars.
As stars age, their speed of rotation decreases.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of each star by determining the time between the appearance of a recognizable region of the star, such as a sunspot.
The latest catalogue of the speed of rotation of stars shows that larger stars rotate slower than smaller stars.
Rebul compares stars to dancers, larger dancers perform pyrues slower than small dancers.
Rebul says that the Pleiadian ballet shows that slowly rotating objects are larger and more massive, while faster rotating objects are very small stars.
Due to its close proximity, the Plejadic constellation serves as a great space laboratory where the characteristics of the stars can be compared to the speed of rotation.
Rebul says that the Plejadic constellation helps to build theoretical models for the rotation of stars in both directions for both older and younger stars.
We still have a lot to learn about how, when and why stars slow down, and about their complete stopping process.
Rebul and his colleagues detailed the analysis of the speed of rotation of the Plejadic stars in three new publications that will soon be published in the Journal of Astronomy.
